full text doc: dr holcomb goes above and beyond to care for her patients. i'm still in awe of my experience with her during hurricane barry. if you can imagine, the night before the storm is supposed to make landfall, i find several lesions on my 11 yr old. i panic because everything is closed! i attempt to contact her via the patient portal but can't find my password. luckily, i find an old email from her office and respond asking for an on call physician and help!! i thought at best i could take her to urgent care the next day but to my surprise i got a reply. not just any reply, a response from dr holcomb herself! just having your doctor respond, while she's caring for her family during a storm, speaks volumes of the importance of patient care to her. she ruled out several things by picture and told me how to care for my little one until the storm blew over. on sunday, yes the weekend, she checked her schedule and told me there was a small opening where she could squeeze us in. i breathed a very heavy sigh of relief and my daughter is fine. i still think of her kindness and willingness to help us during an emergency weather event. sometimes doctors do their jobs but

full text doc: this is a gem of a restaurant located in the middle of a bustling shopping strip on east broadway. i would argue that they might quite possibly serve the best pizza in town. even better, everything they serve here is amazing. if you are looking for an authentic new york style pizza, you're in luck, because this is the closest you will get to having in in tucson. the crust, cheese, and sauce are all on point. i also suggest that you try a slice with hatch chilies on it for an added kick. everything else is great as well. i have tried the garlic knots, cheese sticks, and meatballs. all of which tasted great and of which were crafted with love and care by the staff. oh, have i not mentioned the staff? the staff here is fantastic. they not only provide great customer service here, but they have a lot of pride in their work. upon hearing me praise their crust, one staff member beamed with pride, and told me how the way they prepare the dough was different than the way most places tend to do it. i was riveted. if you are looking for a great pizza place in tucson, look no further.

full text doc: this is your quintessential south jersey diner. the gem of a sj diner is that it is so versatile. sunday breakfast to cure a hangover after a late night? pancakes for dinner on a tuesday? a group that can't agree on a place to eat? need food and need it now? the swedesboro diner is sure to satisfy. this is the place you come to when you want decent food for a decent price at rapid speed ( yes, another perk of diners - food comes out fast ). the menu is extensive, ranging from eggs your way ( i. e. scrambled, sunny - side, poached... nothing too fancy ) to chicken parm ( my dad's favorite ). my go - tos : the turkey club, any of their paninis, and the spinach and feta omelet. if you have a sweet tooth, the swedesboro diner's got you covered - check out their display case of cakes and pies. ( or, if you order an entree, you get free pudding! it doesn't get more diner than this! ) as far as food quality - it's exactly what you expect from a diner. diner food

full text doc: i've purchased cigars from thompson for 10 years - buying mainly online but a few times from their tampa retail outlet. the quality of cigars are as good as from local stores for the same item. i order 20 to 30 cigars per order with about 6 orders per year, so i have 60 or so orders of experience. i have needed to contact customer service only twice. with standard shipping my orders take 5 to 7 days to arrive. on one occasion it took 2 weeks but this was due to ups misrouting. on another order i thought package had been lost - turned out my wife had put in closet and forgot to tell me. both times polite thompson staff were helpful and provided options on how to handle the situations. i don't belong to the cigar club which changes a monthly fee and to which negative reviewers seem to have inadvertently joined. the web site pushes it, so be careful not to sign up unless you really want to become a member.

full text doc: stay away from this place!!! i took my car in for its annual inspection. i had a coupon which allowed me to get state and emission inspection for 39. 99. after the inspection the manager approached me with two separate invoices. the first bill said i needed 2 rear wheel cylinders and brake fluid. the bill for parts and labor was almost $ 600. 00 i was told this amount would have to be paid in order to pass the safety inspection. the second bill was for brake shoes, brake drum and hardware parts. that bill totaled 500. 00 for parts and labor. i was told by the manager that these parts were not urgent and could wait. both bills totaled over $ 1000. 00. i refused service and went to a reputable mechanic in my area the same day. he did the labor of replacing 2 rear cylinders, rear brake shoes and adding brake fluid for a total price of $ 243. 00. you can imagine how shocked i was to think this place was going to rip me off by an additional $ 800. 00. shame on you!!! please remember to always get a second opinion if the price of repairs sounds too high.

full text doc: i've been eating at olympia since i was a child. not only are the flavors authentic but the atmosphere is a perfect blend of formal and fun. whether you're there for a family gathering or a romantic first date, the must have flaming cheese ( saganaki ) and a shot of ouzo is sure it make for a fun and memorable evening. i recommend the hummus first and foremost. a simple yet effective recipe yes, but the texture is divine. for dinner you can't miss the greek salad. if you're having an entree a side salad will do. don't ask about dressings because they only offer the only one you need, greek dressing. for your entree the lamb kebob medium rare is a must have and arguably one of the strongest dishes in st. louis. a bite with pita bread, rice, veggies, and lamb have me craving it far more than i can make it in. finish off with the rice pudding. just do it. young or old, it'll make you feel like a kid again. can't wait to be back!

full text doc: i love that there are so many different kinds of parks in carmel. hazel landing park skews more toward adults, because it's mainly just for frisbee golf / disc golf ( or frolf, if you're into portmanteau ). there is a big, open field and then a few winding trails that meander into the woods. that's where the disc golf goals are located. it's a very peaceful, beautiful, well - kept, isolated park that's a great place to visit, even just to sit and unwind. there are several picnic benches scattered around, so even if you're not a frolfer, you can just come here to relax and eat your lunch in peace. this park is also a landing for boats, hence the " landing " part of the park's name. there is a big ramp that dips into the white river, where you can unload your boat and set sail into the murky waters. there are no official restrooms here, just one port - a - potty.

full text doc: lunch at cindy's was a spur of the moment decision. sometimes in those decisions you find a real gem. cindy's is a small, casual eatery that serves breakfast and lunch. the decor is key west / beach theme and is so cute and comfortable. the service was excellent. we got a chance to speak with kelly the owner. she was a real pip and fun to talk to. our lunch was very good. we started with the broccoli cheddar soup which was rich and creamy. the fish taco's were large and packed with white fish and mango salsa. the ranch lime dressing was tangy and really complemented the fish. the burger with mango salsa and pineapple was a totally different experience for me. the sweetness of the fruit combined with the saltiness of the burger made a perfect combo of flavors. the fries are air cooked so they are crispy but not greasy. my stomach was grateful. we will definitely be back to try breakfast and for our next lunch at cindy's we plan to try the pulled pork and crabby mac and cheese. it looked fantastic!!!

full text doc: the french quarter is just so intriguing. it gives nola a feel like no other city i've ever been in. the historical architecture, restored and renovated bars and restaurants, and iconic locations like jackson square make my wanderlust go mad with happiness. the french quarter dates from the early 1700s and is the oldest neighborhood in new orleans. it stretches 13 blocks from canal street to the mississippi river and ends at esplanade ave. beginning as a french colony, it includes jackson square and the rebuilt st. louis cathedral. it draws cultural influence from its original french heritage, caribbean colonial architecture ( including the famous balconies and paint hues ) introduced during the spanish rule, and finally creole cajun influence in food and music. i highly recommend a ghost tour and a historical tour. visiting the square and the cathedral are a must, and of course you better be getting all of the creole cajun snackas you can get your paws on. the restaurants and street food are unparalleled and the french market is worth a gander as well. of course bourbon st. is a must which became known for vice especially after wwii and continues to be the most famous strip, especially during carnival. if you're visiting new orleans and not visiting

full text doc: if you're looking to fill the nam son shaped void in your heart, or for vietnamese food on this side of broad and further north than washington, the breakfast den is a great option. it's not a full service traditional vietnamese restaurant but it does combine 2 of my favorite things - breakfast and vietnamese food. it's fusion, but a banh mi is fusion ( french viet ), and i'm definitely here for the further multiculturalization of food. if it helps lure people from center city to washington by opening their eyes to the incrediblemess of vietnamese food by disguising it at brunch so we preserve more vietnamese shopping plazas, i'm for that too. i used my parents helping me move as an excuse to get takeout and they loved it. the super soft opening menu has several different sections - apps ( mostly little fried things you dip in sauces ), drinks ( the lavender lemonade is amazing and the vietnamese iced coffee is great too ), sweet stuff ( pancakes and french toast sticks! ), sandwiches ( some banh mi takes and some more fun breakfast sammies ), rice bowls ( choose a protein ) and salads ( which can be wrapped in rice paper ). my dad stopped mid bite

full text doc: much hyped and anticipated new steak place. we went today and realizing they just opened, i'll give them a pass on the phones not working. and also a pass on not having the advertised seeded rolls. the staff was quite frantic trying to get orders and customers straight. and the payment station automatically starts the tip suggestion at 18 % and it goes up from there. hopefully these are all issues they can overcome. now the food - don't believe the pictures on the website. the sandwiches we ordered were more bread than meat. the meat itself was bland and had the occasional chunks of chewy gristle. the fried onions were almost impossible to find and were extremely small pieces. cheese, what there was, was hidden under the meat. the lettuce on the hoagie was no more than a tablespoon on the entire sandwich. the tomatoes were about 1 1 / 2 " in diameter so not sure what kind they were, but there were 2 small discs on one half of the sandwich and none on the other. on the positive side, the veggie steak had a mushroom like taste and was very passable. overall - low marks. but i will give it a second chance to allow for start up issues.

full text doc: for anyone and everyone who appreciates top tier uni, this is the place to get it! my wife and i picked up a couple trays along with cracked stone crab legs and jonah crab salad. everything was excellent, but my goodness the uni was outstanding - creamy with the softest of briny flavors, its freshness was evidenced by the lack of any of that pungency or sharp, almost metallic flavor that's found in lower tier japanese restaurants. on our return trip the next day, we had a chance to try freshly shucked uni on the half shell at ~ $ 13 each. wow, the sea urchin's internal juices seriously amplified all the flavors and created an explosion of briny sweetness and umami that blew me away! to pair, we picked up trays of mad fresh bluefin tuna and scallop sashimi along with scottish salmon poke. all crazy delectable and the poke's flavors were most pleasantly mild. covid precautions were well enforced with only 4 individuals or 2 parties allowed inside at a time. the staff was welcoming and helpful as well, offering to crack and prep those crab legs for us to eat outside.

full text doc: i was really disappointed to see a good number of shoppers in the store today without face masks on, despite the mandate for masks due to covid - 19. there are only 3 legitimate reasons that someone is " medically excused " from wearing a face mask : if they are under the age of 2, if they are unconscious / incapacitated, or if they have severe breathing difficulties ( i. e. - they need supplemental oxygen ). the people i saw shopping sans masks today met none of these criteria. one particularly obnoxious example was a tall, perfectly healthy - appearing blonde woman yapping away on her cell phone while her daughter ( who looked to be about 8 or 9 ) was bouncing along beside her - neither of them was wearing a mask, and for all the rest of knows, they could be asymptomatic carriers. the store manager should be more concerned about the safety of his / her staff and customers - don't be bullied by some entitled self - absorbed nitwit claiming that she " doesn't have to disclose her medical condition " - the law actually states that you can refuse service as long as reasonable accommodations are made, such as offering curbside pickup. not sure i'll be shopping here again
